08266nam a22019695i 9780691224954DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912249547 a10.1515/97806912249542doi  a(DE-B1597)589321  a(OCoLC)1290020663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0550002bisacsh1 aPfeifer, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmpire of Salons :bConquest and Community in Early Modern Ottoman Lands /cHelen Pfeifer. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b18 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on usage -- tIntroduction -- tChapter one. A World Divided -- tChapter two. An Empire Connecting -- tChapter three. A Place in the Elite -- tChapter four. The Art of Conversation -- tChapter five. The Transmission of Knowledge -- tChapter six. An Empire Polarized -- tConclusion -- tAppendix. Key Figures -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA history of the Ottoman incorporation of Arab lands that shows how gentlemanly salons shaped culture, society, and governanceHistorians have typically linked Ottoman imperial cohesion in the sixteenth century to the bureaucracy or the sultan’s court. In Empire of Salons, Helen Pfeifer points instead to a critical but overlooked factor: gentlemanly salons. Pfeifer demonstrates that salons—exclusive assemblies in which elite men displayed their knowledge and status—contributed as much as any formal institution to the empire’s political stability. These key laboratories of Ottoman culture, society, and politics helped men to build relationships and exchange ideas across the far-flung Ottoman lands. Pfeifer shows that salons played a central role in Syria and Egypt’s integration into the empire after the conquest of 1516–17.Pfeifer anchors her narrative in the life and network of the star scholar of sixteenth-century Damascus, Badr al-Dīn al-Ghazzī (d. 1577), and she reveals that Arab elites were more influential within the empire than previously recognized. Their local knowledge and scholarly expertise competed with, and occasionally even outshone, that of the most powerful officials from Istanbul. Ultimately, Ottoman culture of the era was forged collaboratively, by Arab and Turkophone actors alike.Drawing on a range of Arabic and Ottoman Turkish sources, Empire of Salons illustrates the extent to which magnificent gatherings of Ottoman gentlemen contributed to the culture and governance of empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aAssociations, institutions, etczTurkeyxHistoryy16th century. 0aPolitical culturezTurkeyxHistoryy16th century. 0aSalonszEgyptxHistoryy16th century. 0aSalonszSyriazDamascasxHistoryy16th century. 0aSalonszTurkeyzIstanbulxHistoryy16th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aAbu Hayyan al-Gharnati.  aAbu Nuwas.  aAhmad.  aAl-Suyuti.  aAl-Tirmidhi.  aAl-Zamakhshari.  aArabic.  aArabs.  aAvicenna.  aBaths of Caracalla.  aBayezid II.  aBiographical dictionary.  aBook of Judges.  aBurhan al-Din al-Marghinani.  aByzantine Empire.  aCalligraphy.  aClassical Arabic.  aCoffeehouse.  aConstantinople.  aCosmopolitanism.  aDeclamation.  aDisputation.  aDivan.  aEpigram.  aErudition.  aEtiquette.  aExegesis.  aFatih.  aFisc.  aGeorge Clooney.  aGlobal city.  aGog and Magog.  aGrand Vizier.  aGrandee.  aHadith studies.  aHadith.  aHafez.  aHanafi.  aHassan ibn Thabit.  aIbn Hajar al-Asqalani.  aIbn Khalli